# roles/ — durable role charters for this deployment

This directory holds per-role CHARTER files for THIS deployment (`__PROJECT_NAME__`,
scaffolded __CREATED_AT__) -- the static half of
design/FABLE-ROLE-CHARTERS-AND-BRIEFS-SPEC.md (in the autoharn checkout this deployment was
scaffolded from): what a role IS -- responsibilities, scope, constraints -- in the register a
fresh instance reads first.

## Current state: EMPTY

No role charter has been registered yet. This is the honest empty state, not an error --
scaffolding this directory does NOT itself register anything (this is an additive,
NO-LINEAGE-CONTACT scaffold step: it writes a directory and this README, nothing more; no
kernel act, no ledger row).

## The register-before-binding rule

A file sitting in this directory is NOT a charter until it is REGISTERED: the ledger is the
sole authority on which charter text is in force for a role, never a loose file's mere
presence here. Register one with (from this deployment's own root):

```
python3 <autoharn>/tools/role_charter.py register <role> roles/<role>/CHARTER.md
```

(`<role>` must already be a registered `led` principal -- `./led register-principal <role>
<class> --purpose "..."` first, if it is not.) `role_charter.py`'s own `show`/`amend`
subcommands read/supersede that registration; see its module docstring (in the autoharn
checkout: `tools/role_charter.py`) for the full convention, including the loud DRIFT warning
`show` prints when a registered file's on-disk bytes no longer match the hash that was
registered.

The dynamic counterpart -- what a role FACES right now, derived fresh at every instantiation,
never authored -- is `tools/role_brief.py brief <role>`, in the same checkout.

